doc.after: In 2010, Sudan was considered the 17th-fastest-growing economy[105] in the world and the rapid development of the country largely from oil profits even when facing international sanctions was noted by The New York Times in a 2006 article.[106] Over a four-year period to 2014, the Sudanese government's budget was yearly on the order of Â£140M, while UKAid provided Â£30M to Â£54M per annum.[107] Because of the secession of South Sudan, which contained over 80 percent of Sudan's oilfields, the economic forecast for Sudan in 2011 and beyond is uncertain.
